SIMPLE: troll
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Troll
<hw>Troll</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel. <ets>troll</ets>.
Cf. <er>Droll</er>, <er>Trull</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Scand. Myth.)</fld>
<def>A supernatural being, often represented as of diminutive size, but
sometimes as a giant, and fabled to inhabit caves, hills, and like
places; a witch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Troll flower</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>Same as
<er>Globeflower</er> <sd>(a)</sd>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Troll</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Troll
<hw>Troll</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Trolled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Trolling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>trollen</ets> to roll,
F. <ets>tr⟦ocir⟧ler</ets>, Of. <ets>troller</ets> to drag about, to
ramble; probably of Teutonic origin; cf. G. <ets>trollen</ets> to roll,
ramble, sich <ets>trollen</ets> to be gone; or perhaps for
<ets>trotler</ets>, fr. F. <ets>trotter</ets> to trot (cf.
<er>Trot</er>.). Cf. <er>Trawl</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To move
circularly or volubly; to roll; to turn.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To dress and <qex>troll</qex> the tongue, and roll the eye.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To send about; to circulate, as a vessel in
drinking.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then doth she <qex>troll</qex> to the bowl.</q> <rj><qau>Gammer
Gurton's Needle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Troll</qex> the brown bowl.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To sing the parts of in succession, as of a round, a
catch, and the like; also, to sing loudly or freely.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Will you <qex>troll</qex> the catch ?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His sonnets charmed the attentive crowd,⟦br⟧
By wide-mouthed mortal<qex>trolled</qex> aloud.</q>
<rj><qau>Hudibras.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To angle for with a trolling line, or with a book
drawn along the surface of the water; hence, to allure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To fish in; to seek to catch fish from.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With patient angle <qex>trolls</qex> the finny deep.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Troll</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Troll
<hw>Troll</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To roll; to run about;
to move around; <as>as, to <ex>troll</ex> in a coach and
six</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move rapidly; to wag.</def> <rj><au>F.
Beaumont.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To take part in trolling a song.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To fish with a rod whose line runs on a reel; also,
to fish by drawing the hook through the water.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their young men . . . <qex>trolled</qex> along the brooks that
abounded in fish.</q> <rj><qau>Bancroft.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Troll</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Troll
<hw>Troll</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of moving round;
routine; repetition.</def> <rj><au>Burke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A song the parts of which are sung in succession; a
catch; a round.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thence the catch and <qex>troll</qex>, while ⟦ldquo⟧Laughter,
holding both his sides,⟦rdquo⟧ sheds tears to song and ballad pathetic
on the woes of married life.</q> <rj><qau>Prof. Wilson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A trolley.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Troll plate</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a rotative
disk with spiral ribs or grooves, by which several pieces, as the jaws
of a chuck, can be brought together or spread radially.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Troller</ent>⟦br⟧
